Anthropologist [[Emiko Ohnuki-Tierney]] lists three factors that identify Sarutahiko as a [[Monkeys in Japanese culture#Religion|monkey deity]]: ''saru'' means "monkey", his features "include red buttocks, which are a prominent characteristic of Japanese macaques", and as macaques gather shellfish at low tide, the ''[[Kojiki]]'' says his hand got caught in a shell while fishing and "a monkey with one hand caught in a shell is a frequent theme of Japanese folktales".<ref>Ohnuki-Tierney, Emiko (1987), ''The Monkey as Mirror: Symbolic Transformations in Japanese History and Ritual'', Princeton University Press, pp. 42-43.</ref>
==Title== {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|en|4=fr|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt=Sarutahiko|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sarutahiko Ōkami|qq=}} has the distinction of being one of only seven {{ill|kami|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kami|qq=}} to be honored with the title '''Ōkami''' ({{CJKV|j=大神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) or "Great Kami"; the other six are [[Izanagi]], {{ill|Izanami|en|lt=Izanami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanami|qq=}}, {{ill|Dōsojin|en|4=ja|5=道祖神|6=fr|7=Dōsojin|8=en:draft|9=Michikaeshi Ōkami|10=simple|11=User:Immanuelle/Dōsojin|lt=Michikaeshi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dōsojin|qq=}} (also known as Yomido ni sayarimasu ōkami (?) who is the kami of the great rock used by Izanagi to obstruct the way to Yomi, and thus, preventing emergence of evil spirits from the Underworld), {{ill|Sashikuni Ōkami|ja|刺国大神|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni_Okami|8=fr|lt=Sashikuni|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni Ōkami|qq=}}, {{ill|Inari Ōkami|en|lt=Inari|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inari Ōkami|qq=}}, and {{ill|Amaterasu|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|qq=}}. Sarutahiko and Inari appear to be the only Okami from the ''kunitsukami'', or earthly kami, the others being ''{{ill|Amatsukami|en|4=fr|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amatsukami|qq=}}'' (heavenly deities). Although there is some other Daimyōjin and Daigongen, most of them appeared later in the History of Japanese Religion, such as [[Hachiman]] (deification of [[Empress Jingū|Empress Jingu]], [[Emperor Ōjin|Emperor Ojin]] and maybe [[Takenouchi no Sukune]], as a successful head of state) or Hindu deities, the meaning of Daimyōjin appear to be a little different from Ōkami, the latter being obviously more ancient. <ref>{{Cite web|title=Kami – OCCULT WORLD|url=https://occult-world.com/kami/|access-date=2024-03-19|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Better source}}
==References in music== The name of this deity appears incorrectly spelled as "Sarundasico" in [[Puccini]]'s opera ''[[Madama Butterfly]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=2004 Regular Opera Performance "Madama Butterfly / revised edition"|url=http://www.minna-no-opera.com/eng/opera/2004_btt_gui_e.htm|publisher=NPO Opera del Popolo|access-date=13 August 2012}}</ref>
