Sarutahiko Ōkami is seen as a symbol of [[Misogi]], strength and guidance, which is why he is the patron of [[Japanese martial arts|martial arts]] such as [[:en:Aikido|Aikido]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gleason|first=William|title=The Spiritual Foundations of Aikido|year=1995|publisher=Destiny Books|isbn=0-89281-508-6|pages=18|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S4JRDf6C4iMC&pg=PA18}}</ref> He is enshrined at [[Tsubaki Grand Shrine]] in [[:en:Mie Prefecture|Mie Prefecture]]; first among the 2000 shrines of Sarutahiko Ōkami, Sarutahiko Jinja in [[:en:Ise, Mie|Ise, Mie]]; and [[:en:Ōasahiko Shrine|Ōasahiko Shrine]] in [[Tokushima Prefecture]], and [[Sarutahiko Shrine]] in Mie Prefecture. In the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', he is the one who meets [[Ninigi-no-Mikoto]], the grandson of [[Amaterasu]], the Sun goddess, when he descends from [[Takamagahara|Takama-ga-hara]].<ref>{{cite web|title=English|url=http://www.sarutahiko-jinjya.net/img/panf_e.pdf|publisher=尾張猿田彦神社|access-date=14 August 2012}}</ref> He is depicted as a towering man with a large beard, jeweled spear, ruddy face, and long nose. At first he is unwilling to let Ninigi pass until persuaded by [[Ame-no-Uzume|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto]], the kami of dance and the arts, whom he later marries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shrine History|url=http://www.tsubakishrine.org/history/index.html|publisher=Tsubaki Grand Shrine America|access-date=13 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Roberts|first=Jeremy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdfgjV2kw6oC&q=Ninigi|title=Japanese Mythology A to Z|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-2802-3|language=en}}</ref> Even Sarutahiko was regarded as the "god who illuminates the sky and the earth" in Ise, and was worshiped by local believers as the '''sun god''' (personification of sun) before [[Amaterasu]].
He, Ame-no-Uzume and their children subsequently created the ''{{ill|Sarume clan|ja|猿女君|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sarume clan|qq=}}'' (猿女の君) clan along with an order of female court and religious dancers.<ref name="picken-2004a">{{Cite book |last=Picken |first=Stuart D. B. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BKAhUVqKFhgC&q=Uzume&pg=PA1 |title=Sourcebook in Shinto: Selected Documents |date=2004 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-313-26432-0 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="roberts-2009a">{{Cite book |last=Roberts |first=Jeremy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdfgjV2kw6oC&q=Uzume |title=Japanese Mythology A to Z |date=2009 |publisher=Infobase Publishing |isbn=978-1-4381-2802-3 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="coulter-2013a">{{Cite book |last1=Coulter |first1=Charles Russell |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VWxekbhM1yEC&dq=Ame-no-Uzume&pg=PT91 |title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Deities |last2=Turner |first2=Patricia |date=2013-07-04 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-96397-2 |language=en}}</ref> It was the origin of [[Kagura]] and [[Noh]]. Other descendants includes the Ujitoko clan from Ise province. According to Kojiki, he went in Ise where a giant clam trapped his hand on [[Isuzu River|Isuzu river]] at Azaka, thus he drowned. But strangely, Sarutahiko was considered by [[Ueshiba Morihei]] as a kind of god of the cosmic life: the god of Aiki. According to O-Senseï, the practice of [[:en:Aikidō|Aikidō]] was practice of [[Misogi]] purification itself ("and thus, like Sarutahiko standing of ''Ame-no-Ukibashi'', standing between Heaven and Earth, being one with the Universe, and so achieving peace with the world, the next step being World Peace itself"){{cn|date=May 2023}}
